<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1926-11-07T23:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1926-11-07T23:00:00-05:00" n="513" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d513">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">893.00/7810: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">MacMurray</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Peking</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1926-11-08T12:00:00+08:00"><hi rend="italic">November 8,
                                        1926—noon</hi></date>.<lb/>[Received November 8—2:48
                                a.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>534. My 553 [<hi rend="italic">533</hi>], November 6, 11 a.m. Following
                            from American consul general, Hankow: <quote rend="blockquote">
                                <p>“November 6, 1 p.m. American naval radio from Kiukiang this
                                    morning states city quiet and completely occupied by Southern
                                    troops, <pb facs="0783" n="651" xml:id="pg_651"/> practically
                                    all Northerners having been evacuated down river. Japanese and
                                    American landing forces withdrawn. Fighting reported in vicinity
                                    of Wusüeh.”</p>
                            </quote></p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">MacMurray</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>